    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.36-37_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">36</fw>
                    
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THOMAS S. JONES, JR.
                        <lb/>
                    411 WEST 115TH STREET
                        <lb/>
                    NEW YORK CITY</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>October 17, 1929</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>My dear friend,</salute> 
                </opener>
                <p>I am enclosing a copy of a letter that I have just received from my friend Woodford Patterson, secretary of Cornell, my own college. It speaks for itself, and for the vibrations of power that you have sent out. How grateful I am to you!</p>
                    
                <p>By this time you have my letter of deep happiness because of your article, and the request for six clippings from the paper. I was able to pick up four copies here: two of the Friday issue, and two from the Saturday paper!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Thomas S. Jones, Jr.</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
            <div1  type="enclosure">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.36-37_0002"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">37</fw>
                
                <note>(COPY)</note>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        3 Central Avenue
                        Ithaca, New York
                    
                        16 October 1929
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Tom:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you for your note of the 15th and the clipping of Mr. Neihardt's review, which I have copied off carefully for my own preservation, and now return to you with my hearty congratulations &#8212;&#8212; no, I will not say congratulations, for that is too chilly a word: I will say joy &#8212;&#8212; joy in having read so wise and discerning and true an interpretation of your poetry by a man whose own poetry I have learned to treasure. When he says that "yours is the music that we who are dea<del>d</del><add>f</add>ened by this loud moment need desperately to hear," testifying to the sensitiveness of his own inner ear, he proves to me that I have not been deluded when I felt in reading your Sonnets "as though the mystery of the world were suddenly realized as unutterably holy." I thank him for that phrase. In the course of reading your poetry as it has appeared in the course of the last eleven years, I have come to realize that my own world has been transformed &#8212;&#8212; lit up and populated in regions that were dark before. In w<del/><add>ha</add>t he says at the beginning of his review, Mr. Neihardt sets himself at the height of an Alp above the level of today's fashion of criticism &#8212;&#8212; and at an Alp plus an oceanic deep above George Moore's level.</p>
                    
                <p>The Alumni News will wait for my article &#8212;&#8212; and not long.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Woodford Patterson</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
